{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":300407,"duration_api_ms":293037,"num_turns":44,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"972926fe-7136-466f-87bc-4923fa3715e9","total_cost_usd":1.52142525,"usage":{"input_tokens":1506,"cache_creation_input_tokens":55968,"cache_read_input_tokens":1730814,"output_tokens":10257,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":55968,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":1507,"outputTokens":10515,"cacheReadInputTokens":1771268,"cacheCreationInputTokens":58461,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":1.52142525,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"amendments":[{"body":"In the snapshot write error recovery path (engine.rs ~line 4657-4683), if `fail_run`'s own snapshot write at line 5133 also fails (e.g. persistent disk I/O error), the `?` propagates the error without emitting a `run_failed` journal event and without any snapshot reaching disk — potentially leaving the project in an inconsistent state where the journal has a `stage_failed` event but the on-disk snapshot is stale. Consider wrapping `fail_run`'s snapshot write in a best-effort fallback (e.g. log the double-failure and still emit the journal event), or at minimum add a comment documenting this known limitation and why it's acceptable.","rationale":"The whole purpose of this change is to prevent the run from getting stranded in an unresumable state when a snapshot write fails. But the recovery path routes to `fail_run` which itself uses `?` on its snapshot write (line 5133). If the disk is persistently failing (not just a transient blip), the recovery path hits the same wall. The test only covers the case where the second write succeeds (the `BackoffFailingSnapshotWriteStore` discriminates by status_summary). While persistent disk failures are inherently hard to handle, the code should at least document this edge case since the entire change is motivated by snapshot-write resilience."}],"summary":"The diff contains two changes: (1) a jitter counter improvement in retry_policy.rs that adds a thread-local monotonic counter to ensure distinct jitter values on coarse-clock platforms, and (2) error handling for pre-backoff snapshot writes in engine.rs that routes write failures through `fail_run_result` instead of bare `?`, preventing the run from being stranded in an unresumable Running state. Both changes are well-reasoned. The state restoration logic (lines 4660-4663) correctly undoes the Failed/None mutations so `fail_run_result` can re-attempt. The jitter counter uses standard wrapping arithmetic with Knuth's multiplicative hash. The new test properly validates the behavior under `test-stub` feature flag and passes. The one substantive concern is that `fail_run` itself uses `?` on its snapshot write, so a persistent disk failure would bypass the journal event — the exact class of problem this change aims to prevent."},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"5045c691-3c73-4ff8-9b1f-44a89f6b8ffd"}
